<ArticleLayout
  title="Small Kitchen Appliances: What to Check Before You Buy"
  description="Before buying a small kitchen appliance, check bench space, storage, power point access, cleaning effort, size, weight and whether it will genuinely make daily cooking easier."
  category="Kitchen"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="8 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/kitchen.webp"
  imageAlt="A warm kitchen with timber cabinetry, green accents and practical appliance storage"
>
  <p>
    Small kitchen appliances can be useful, but they can also take over a kitchen quickly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Air fryers, coffee machines, blenders, mixers, rice cookers, sandwich presses, slow
    cookers, food processors and benchtop ovens all need space. Some need regular cleaning.
    Some are awkward to lift. Some are used every day. Others are used a few times and then
    pushed to the back of a cupboard.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying another appliance, it is worth checking whether it will genuinely make the
    kitchen easier to use.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide explains what to measure and check before buying a small kitchen appliance,
    especially for Australian homes, rentals, apartments and smaller kitchens.
  </p>
  <p>
    For broader storage planning, see our main guide:
    <a href="/guides/best-kitchen-storage-ideas-small-australian-homes/">Kitchen Storage: What to Measure and Check Before You Buy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with the job, not the appliance</h2>
  <p>
    Before buying an appliance, identify the actual job it needs to do.
  </p>
  <p>A small appliance may be useful if it solves a regular problem, such as:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Cooking quick meals.</li>
    <li>Making breakfast easier.</li>
    <li>Preparing school lunches.</li>
    <li>Reducing oven use.</li>
    <li>Making coffee at home.</li>
    <li>Blending smoothies.</li>
    <li>Cooking rice regularly.</li>
    <li>Batch cooking.</li>
    <li>Chopping ingredients.</li>
    <li>Reheating food.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    It may be less useful if it only solves a rare problem or duplicates something already in
    the kitchen.
  </p>
  <p>
    For example, a food processor may be helpful in a household that cooks from scratch often.
    It may be unnecessary if most chopping is simple and occasional. A rice cooker may be
    useful if rice is cooked several times a week. It may not be worth the storage space if it
    is used once a month.
  </p>
  <p>
    The better question is not "Is this appliance good?" The better question is "Will this
    appliance earn its space in this kitchen?"
  </p>

  <h2>Check available bench space</h2>
  <p>
    Some appliances are only useful if they can stay on the bench.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying, measure the space where the appliance would realistically sit.
  </p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Bench width.</li>
    <li>Bench depth.</li>
    <li>Height under overhead cupboards.</li>
    <li>Space beside the sink.</li>
    <li>Space near power points.</li>
    <li>Whether cupboard doors can still open.</li>
    <li>Whether the appliance blocks food preparation space.</li>
    <li>Whether the appliance needs room around it when used.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A compact appliance can still be annoying if it permanently removes your only useful
    preparation area.
  </p>
  <p>
    For small kitchens, the most important storage decision may be what does not live on the
    bench.
  </p>
  <p>
    Daily-use appliances may deserve bench space. Occasional appliances usually need a storage
    plan.
  </p>

  <h2>Check appliance height and cupboard clearance</h2>
  <p>
    Appliance height matters, especially in kitchens with overhead cupboards.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Appliance height.</li>
    <li>Height with the lid open.</li>
    <li>Height with attachments fitted.</li>
    <li>Height under overhead cupboards.</li>
    <li>Whether steam or heat rises near cabinets.</li>
    <li>Whether the appliance can be used safely in that position.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>This is especially important for appliances with lids, doors or moving parts, such as:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Air fryers.</li>
    <li>Coffee machines.</li>
    <li>Stand mixers.</li>
    <li>Rice cookers.</li>
    <li>Slow cookers.</li>
    <li>Blenders.</li>
    <li>Benchtop ovens.</li>
    <li>Food processors.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    An appliance may fit on the bench but still be awkward if the lid cannot open properly or
    steam rises directly into overhead cabinetry.
  </p>

  <h2>Check storage space before buying</h2>
  <p>
    If the appliance will not stay on the bench, decide where it will live.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure the cupboard, shelf or pantry space before buying.
  </p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Cupboard width.</li>
    <li>Cupboard depth.</li>
    <li>Shelf height.</li>
    <li>Door opening width.</li>
    <li>Whether the appliance can be lifted in and out safely.</li>
    <li>Whether the cord stores neatly.</li>
    <li>Whether attachments need separate storage.</li>
    <li>Whether the appliance is too heavy for high shelves.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A heavy appliance stored above shoulder height is not practical for many households. It may
    technically fit, but it will be inconvenient and potentially unsafe to move.
  </p>
  <p>
    If an appliance is difficult to access, it is less likely to be used.
  </p>

  <h2>Check weight and handling</h2>
  <p>
    Weight matters more than people expect.
  </p>
  <p>
    Some appliances are compact but heavy. Others are bulky, awkward or have parts that fall
    loose when moved.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, consider:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Appliance weight.</li>
    <li>Handle position.</li>
    <li>Whether it can be carried with one hand.</li>
    <li>Whether it needs to be moved often.</li>
    <li>Whether it has loose accessories.</li>
    <li>Whether it is safe to store high.</li>
    <li>Whether the household member using it can lift it comfortably.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This is especially relevant for stand mixers, large air fryers, food processors, pressure
    cookers and benchtop ovens.
  </p>
  <p>
    If an appliance is too heavy to move comfortably, it either needs a permanent bench
    position or it may become unused cupboard clutter.
  </p>

  <h2>Check power point access</h2>
  <p>
    Power point location can affect whether an appliance is convenient.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Whether there is a power point near the intended use area.</li>
    <li>Whether the cord will reach safely.</li>
    <li>Whether the appliance would need an extension cord.</li>
    <li>Whether the cord crosses a sink, cooktop or walkway.</li>
    <li>Whether other appliances already use that power point.</li>
    <li>Whether the appliance can be unplugged easily.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid setting up appliances where cords create trip, heat or water risks.
  </p>
  <p>
    In older kitchens and rentals, power points may be limited or poorly placed. That can make
    some appliances less practical even if there is enough bench space.
  </p>

  <h2>Check cleaning effort</h2>
  <p>
    A small appliance is only useful if the cleaning effort suits the household.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>How many parts need cleaning.</li>
    <li>Whether parts are removable.</li>
    <li>Whether food gets trapped in corners.</li>
    <li>Whether parts can be washed easily.</li>
    <li>Whether filters, trays or seals need regular cleaning.</li>
    <li>Whether the appliance needs drying before storage.</li>
    <li>Whether cleaning takes longer than the task it saves.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Some appliances save cooking time but add cleaning time.
  </p>
  <p>
    That may still be worthwhile for frequent use. It may be frustrating for occasional use.
  </p>
  <p>
    For busy households, simple cleaning often matters more than extra features.
  </p>

  <h2>Check attachments and accessories</h2>
  <p>
    Many appliances come with accessories.
  </p>
  <p>These may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Blades.</li>
    <li>Bowls.</li>
    <li>Lids.</li>
    <li>Trays.</li>
    <li>Racks.</li>
    <li>Measuring cups.</li>
    <li>Beaters.</li>
    <li>Filters.</li>
    <li>Baskets.</li>
    <li>Spare seals.</li>
    <li>Cleaning tools.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Before buying, check where these parts will be stored.
  </p>
  <p>
    Accessories can create clutter if they do not have a clear home. Small pieces may also get
    lost at the back of drawers or cupboards.
  </p>
  <p>
    If an appliance needs several loose parts to work properly, make sure the storage plan
    includes all of them.
  </p>
  <p>
    For drawer-specific planning, see:
    <a href="/guides/kitchen-drawer-storage-what-to-measure-before-buying-organisers/">Kitchen Drawer Storage: What to Measure Before Buying Organisers</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about how often it will be used</h2>
  <p>
    Frequency matters.
  </p>
  <p>
    A daily-use appliance may justify bench space, even if it is large. An occasional
    appliance needs to justify the cupboard space it takes up.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying, be realistic.
  </p>
  <p>Ask:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Will I use this every day?</li>
    <li>Will I use it every week?</li>
    <li>Does it replace another appliance?</li>
    <li>Does it make a common task easier?</li>
    <li>Will it suit the meals I actually cook?</li>
    <li>Will it still be useful after the novelty wears off?</li>
    <li>Do I already own something that does the same job?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    An appliance used once or twice a year may not deserve prime kitchen storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the appliance is for a habit you hope to start, consider whether a smaller or simpler
    option would be safer first.
  </p>

  <h2>Consider renters and small kitchens</h2>
  <p>
    Renters and small-kitchen households need to be especially careful with appliances.
  </p>
  <p>
    In a rental, you may not be able to add shelves, change cabinetry or create a permanent
    appliance station. In a small kitchen, a single large appliance can remove a lot of usable
    bench space.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Whether the appliance can move with you.</li>
    <li>Whether it needs permanent setup.</li>
    <li>Whether it suits limited power points.</li>
    <li>Whether it can be stored without drilling or cabinet changes.</li>
    <li>Whether it blocks already limited preparation space.</li>
    <li>Whether it creates steam, heat or splatter near surfaces you do not own.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For rental-specific planning, see:
    <a href="/guides/renter-friendly-kitchen-storage-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">Renter-Friendly Kitchen Storage: What to Check Before You Buy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Avoid duplicate appliances</h2>
  <p>
    Many kitchens collect appliances that overlap.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying, check whether something you already own can do the same job.
  </p>
  <p>For example:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>A blender and food processor may overlap for some tasks.</li>
    <li>An oven and benchtop oven may overlap.</li>
    <li>A rice cooker and multi-cooker may overlap.</li>
    <li>A sandwich press and grill may overlap.</li>
    <li>A stand mixer and hand mixer may overlap.</li>
    <li>An air fryer and oven may overlap for some households.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Overlap is not always bad. A household may use both appliances for different reasons.
  </p>
  <p>
    But if storage is limited, duplicate functions should be questioned before another
    appliance is added.
  </p>

  <h2>Common small appliance buying mistakes</h2>
  <p>
    Small appliances can become frustrating when the buying decision is based only on
    features.
  </p>
  <p>Common mistakes include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Buying before measuring bench space.</li>
    <li>Forgetting lid or door clearance.</li>
    <li>Ignoring storage space.</li>
    <li>Storing heavy appliances too high.</li>
    <li>Overlooking cleaning effort.</li>
    <li>Buying appliances with too many loose parts.</li>
    <li>Assuming it will stay useful after the novelty wears off.</li>
    <li>Duplicating appliances already owned.</li>
    <li>Ignoring power point location.</li>
    <li>Choosing a large appliance for a small kitchen without a storage plan.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The goal is not to own every useful appliance. The goal is to choose appliances that make
    everyday cooking easier without making the kitchen harder to use.
  </p>

  <h2>When not to buy the appliance yet</h2>
  <p>You may not need to buy the appliance yet if:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>There is no clear place to store it.</li>
    <li>The bench is already crowded.</li>
    <li>The appliance duplicates one you already own.</li>
    <li>It solves a problem you rarely have.</li>
    <li>Cleaning it would be too annoying.</li>
    <li>It is too heavy to move safely.</li>
    <li>The kitchen lacks suitable power point access.</li>
    <li>The purchase is based mainly on a short-term trend.</li>
    <li>You are not sure how often it will be used.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Waiting can be the better decision.
  </p>
  <p>
    It may also help to remove unused appliances first. If the kitchen already contains
    appliances that are rarely used, buying another one may make the storage problem worse.
  </p>

  <h2>Simple small appliance checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying a small kitchen appliance, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>What job will it do?</li>
    <li>How often will it be used?</li>
    <li>Does it duplicate something already owned?</li>
    <li>Where will it live?</li>
    <li>Have I measured the bench or cupboard space?</li>
    <li>Does it fit under overhead cupboards?</li>
    <li>Can the lid, door or attachments open properly?</li>
    <li>Is there safe power point access?</li>
    <li>Is it easy to clean?</li>
    <li>Are there loose accessories to store?</li>
    <li>Is it too heavy to move safely?</li>
    <li>Will it suit a rental or small kitchen if needed?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Small kitchen appliances are most useful when they solve a regular problem and have a
    clear place to live.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure first, check the cleaning and storage needs, and avoid giving permanent kitchen
    space to an appliance that will rarely be used.
  </p>
  <p>
    If pantry storage is part of the same kitchen problem, see:
    <a href="/guides/pantry-storage-what-to-measure-before-buying-organisers/">Pantry Storage: What to Measure Before Buying Organisers</a>.
  </p>

